#X text 258 271 Another common practive is to pass the sound source through an overdrive before filtering \, which changes the spectral content before filtering. In this case we're using a 'tanh' function in drive (a waveshaping distortion)., f 40;
#X text 58 63 Below we have the oscillator section in a subpatch where we use a rich sound that combines a square and a sawtooth oscillator \, hence we have wave stacking \, much like the first example on this series. This is to reinforce how additive synthesis is usually part of what we know as subtractive synthesis. Hence \, we add stuff before filtering (and "subtracting"). Not only that \, but we're also adding some noise \, which is also common in synthesizers and can be of adifferent kinds - usually 'white' and 'pink' \, but this example uses 'brown'. The color of the noise indicates the predominant frequency content. White noise has an equal distribution of frequencies. Pink has a 3dB decay over octaves \, while brown decays at 6dB per octave. Hence \, choosing the kind of noise is like applying a filter to the noise input., f 69;
